A R T I C L E   I N F O   Article history:  Received  Received in revised form  Accepted  Available online  Keywords:  Thioquinomycins A-D    Marine-derived Streptomyces    X-ray diffraction    Cytotoxicity  kinase inhibitory activities    Marine-derived Streptomyces has been proved to be one of the  most  important  genus  that  produce  the  numerous  natural  products.1  Many  bioactive  substances  had been  discovered  from  this  genus,  for  example,  antibiotics,  anticancer  compounds,  and  enzyme  for  most  marine-derived  microorganisms,  their  gene  clusters  (especially  PKS  gene  clusters  and  NRPS  gene  clusters)  which  controlled  secondary  metabolite  syntheses  were  always  silent  under  traditional  culture  conditions.5  In  order  to  obtain  more  active  secondary  metabolites,  a  variety  of  methods  must  be  utilized  to  activate their silent metabolic pathways.6 one single strain could  produce  many  various  compounds  when  grown  in  the  different  conditions,  which  has  been  conceptualized  in  the  “one  strain  many  compounds”(OSMAC).7  These  different  conditions  including temperature, time, medium content, aeration rate and so  on. Among them, one of the simplest and most effective methods  is  the  alteration  of  culture  methods  and  has  gotten  some  achievements.8

Aiming  at  discovering  structurally  diverse  and  potent  bioactive  compounds  from  marine-derived  Strepetomyces  using  different  culture  methods,  the  strain  titled  as  SS17F  which  produced  medermycin  in  traditional  Gause’s  liquid  medium  was  systematically studied. After cultivating in rice-based medium for  one  month,  secondary  metabolites  of  the  strain  showed  many  different peaks based on the analysis of HPLC (Figure S43). The  Tetrahedron  j o u r n a l   h o m e p a g e :   w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m   Thioquinomycins  A-D  (1-4),  four  novel  naphthothiophenediones  were  isolated  from  the  rice-based  medium  of  the  marine-derived  Streptomyces  sp.  SS17F.  Their  structures  were  elucidated by spectroscopic methods and HRESIMS data. The absolute configurations of all the  compounds were elucidated by X-ray diffraction analysis, ECD and Mosher’s method combined  with  19F-NMR.  Compounds  1-4  showed  moderate  cytotoxicity  against  NCI-H1975  with  IC50 values  from  17.5  to  50  µM.  In  addition,  compounds  1-4  also  exhibited  inhibitory  activities  against PKCα and ROCK2 protein kinase.  main  additional  peaks  determined  by  compound  isolation  and  structure  determination  were  four  novel  sulfur-containing  compounds.  2. Results and discussion

Colonies of the strain SS17F growing on Gause’s agar plate were  inoculated into a 500 mL Erlenmeyer flask, containing 250 mL of  Gause’s  liquid  medium,  and  then  incubated  at  28  °C  for  5  days  on  a  rotary  shaker  (180  rpm)  to  produce  seed  broth.  The  seed  broth  was  then  transferred  to  500  mL  Erlenmeyer  flasks,  each  containing  40  g  sterilized  rice  along  with  60  mL  sea  salt  water.  After  incubation  in  static  cultivation  for  30  days  at  28  °C,  an  EtOAc  extract  from  the  cultures  was  fractionated  by  silica  gel  and Sephadex LH-20 column chromatograph and further purified  by preparative HPLC to afford compounds 1-4.  2018 Elsevier Ltd. Thioquinomycin A (1) was obtained as yellow needle crystals  from  methanol.  Its  molecular  formula  was  assigned  to  be  C22H23NO6S,  as  deduced  from  NMR  data  and  the  HR-ESI-MS  ions  at  m/z  428.1170  [M-H]-  (Cal.  428.1173),  indicating  12  degrees  of  unsaturation.  The  strong  absorption  peaks  in  its  IR  spectrum showed the presence of C=O (1675 cm-1) and phenolic  hydroxyl  (3396  cm-1).  The  UV  characteristic  absorptions  (266  and  396  nm)  combined  with  its  physical  properties  suggested  thatcompound  1  might  be  a  conjugated-quinines  structure.  The  1H  and  13C  NMR  spectroscopic  data  (Table  1)  combined  with  HSQC  3,  a  4-tetrasubstituted aromatic ring at δH 7.75 (1H, d, J = 7.9 Hz) and  7.86 (1H, d, J = 7.9 Hz), four methyl groups (δH 1.31, 2.60, 2.71  and  2.93),  one  methylene  (δC  32.5)  and  four  heteratomic  to  methines  angolosamine,  three  ketone  carbonyls  (δC  178.7,  186.8  and  195.3), and eight non- protonated carbons (δC 116.2, 130.9, 133.9,  134.3, 136.3, 145.5, 155.7 and 158.5).

The  structure  was  mainly  constructed  by  the  aid  of  HMBC  correlations.  Firstly,  the  fragment  (i)  of  angolosamine  was  determined by key HMBC correlations from H-2¢  to C-3¢ , H-3¢  to  C-2¢ , C-4¢ , H-5¢  to C-4¢ , C-6¢ , 6¢ -CH3 to C-5¢ , C-6¢  and 4¢ -N-CH3  to C-4¢ ，together with the COSY correlations of H-2¢ /H-3¢ /H-4¢ /  H-5¢ /H-6¢ .  The  structure  of  the  other  fragment  (ii)  was  also  constructed by HMBC cross-peaks from H-7 to C-5, C-8a, H-8 to  C-4a,  C-6,  C-9,  H-11  to  C-1,  C-10  and  H-12  to  C-3,  C-3a,  and  (δC  59.6,  70.3,  71.6  and  76.5)  belonging  C-4  combined  with  COSY  correlations  of  H-7/H-8.  Finally,  the  fragment  i  attached  to  ii  through  C-6  according  to  the  HMBC  correlations  of  H-7/C-2¢   and  H-2¢ /C-5.  Therefore,  the  planar  structure of compound 1 was elucidated as shown in Figure 1.  Figure 1. Key 1H-1H COSY, and HMBC correlations of 1.

The  relative  configuration  of  1  was  assigned  by  the  ROESY  spectrum  (Figure  2).  The  correlations  of  H-2¢ /H-4¢ ,  H-2¢ /H-6¢   and H-4¢ /H-6¢  indicated that H-2¢ , H-4¢  and H-6¢  were located on  the same side. The correlation of H-3¢ b and H-5¢  also suggested  they were located on the opposite side.  The  absolute  configuration  was  firstly  studied  by  ECD,  and  the ECD curve of compound 1 showed the similar characteristics  with  medermycin,  a  known  antibiotic  obtained  with  the  strain  grew  in  traditional  Gause’s  liquid  medium.9  (Figure  S1).  In  addition, we obtained the yellowish needle crystals of compound  1 in methanol with 0.05% trifluoroacetic acid. The single-crystal  X-ray diffraction analysis of 1 was carried out on the Mo Kα and  established  the  absolute  configuration of  1  as  2¢ R, 4¢ R, 5¢ S, 6¢ R.  Overall,  compound  1  was  determined  as  shown  (Figure  3  and  Figure S2).

Thioquinomycin  B  (2)  was  obtained  as  a  yellow  powder.  Its  molecular  formula  was  determined  to  be  C23H25NO6S  on  the  basis  of  HR-ESI-MS  ion  peak  at  m/z  442.1326  [M-H]-.  The  1D  NMR spectroscopic data of 2 were almost identical with 1 except  for  the  presence  of  an  extra  methyl  at  δH  2.80,  as  further  supported  by  HMBC  correlations  (Figure  4).  The  relative  configuration  of  angolosamine  in  2  was  determined  by  the  ROESY  spectrum,  which  shared  the  same  result  with  1  (Figure  2).  The  similar  ECD  curves  between  2  and  1  indicated  that  the  absolute configuration of 2 was consistent with 1. (Figure 5).  Figure 4. Key 1H-1H COSY and HMBC correlations of 2-4.  Figure 2. Key ROESY correlations (dotted line) of 1-4.  Figure 3. ORTEP drawing of 1.

Thioquinomycin  C  (3)  and  D  (4)  were  obtained  as  orange  solid  with  the  molecular  formulas  C22H25NO6S  and  C23H27NO6S  based  on  the  HRESIMS  data.  Their  1H  and  13C  NMR  spectra  were almost similar to 1 and 2, respectively. The main differences  between  them  were  the  absence  of  a  ketone  carbonyl  and  the  presence  of  an  oxygenated  methine  at  C-10  in  3  and  4,  respectively,  which  were  also  confirmed  by  the  key  COSY  correlation  of  H-10/H-11.  The  ROESY  experiments  of  3  and  4  showed that angolosamine shared the same relative configuration  with 1 and 2.    In order to establish the configuration of C-10 on 3 and 4, we  performed  19F-NMR  mosher  method.10  Treatment  of  4  with  (S)-(+)-α-methoxy-α-(trifluoromethyl)phenylacetyl  chloride  [(S)-  (+)-MTPA-Cl] or (R)-(-)-MTPA-Cl gave (R)-MTPA ester 4R and  (S)-MTPA ester 4S，respectively. The 19F-NMR signals of the 4R  derived from the corresponding 4S showed an upfield shift (△δ=  0.03). So the configuration of C-10 was classified as R in 4. The  similar  ECD  spectra  determined  that  the  absolute  configuration  of 3 was the same with 4. (Figure 5).

Compounds  1-4  were  evaluated  for  their  cytotoxicity  against  cancer cells and kinase inhibitory activities of PKCα and ROCK2  based  on  the  CCK-8  method  and  HTRF  kinase  assay.11  The  results indicated that all of them exhibited modest antineoplastic  activity  against  human  non-small  cell  lung  cancer  cells  H1975  (NCI-H1975),  with  IC50  values  of  22.45  µM,  50.72  µM,  17.58  µM  and  20.00  µM,  respectively.  And  they  all  showed  modest  inhibition on PKCα and ROCK2 with IC50 values from 0.64 µM  to 8.89 µM.    Table 2. Cytotoxicity and kinase inhibitory activity of  compounds 1-4  Figure 5. Thioquinomycin A Thioquinomycin B Thioquinomycin C Thioquinomycin D In  summary,  we  present  four  novel  sulfur-containing  natural  the  marine-derived  products  the  extract  of  Streptomyces  sp.  SS17F.  Their  structures  were  elucidated  by  NMR and HRESIMS data. The absolute configurations of all the  compounds were deduced by X-ray diffraction analysis, ECD and  the  Mosher’s  method  combined  with  bioactivities of compounds 1-4 were evaluated and they showed  moderate  cytotoxicity  against  NCI-H1975  and  inhibitory  activities against PKCα and ROCK2 protein kinase.  4.1. General procedures.

Optical rotation was determined on a JASCO DIP-370 digital  polarimetry  (JASCO,  Japan).  CD  spectra  were  collected  on  a  JASCO  J-1500-150ST.  X-ray  diffraction  analysis  was  done  on  the RIGAKU R-AXIS RAPID equipment with Mo Kα radiation.  UV  data  were  obtained  using  METASH  UV-8000s  (Shanghai  METASH Instruments Co. Ltd., China). IR spectra were acquired  on  Bruker  Tensor  27  FT-IR  spectrometer  (Germany).  NMR  spectra were obtained on Bruker AM-600 NMR spectrometer or  Bruker  AM-400  NMR  spectrometer  using  TMS  as  an  internal  standard.  HRESIMS  were  obtained  on  an  Agilent  1260  HPLC-6230  TOF  LC/MS  system  mass  spectrometer.  HPLC  analysis  was  performed  Shimadzu  High-Performance  Liquid  Chromatography  using  Agilent  ODS  column  (10  µm,  4.6  ×  250  mm).  Preparative  HPLC  was  performed  on  Beijing  Chuangxintongheng  LC3000  Semi-preparation  Gradient  HPLC  using an Agilent C18 column (5 µm, 21.2 × 250 mm). Silica gel  (100-200, 300-400 mesh, Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Ltd.),  Sephadex  LH-20  gel  (Uppsala,  Sweden)  were  used  for  column  chromatography  (CC).  Precoated  silica  gel  GF254  plates  (Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Ltd. China) were used for TLC  monitors.  All  solvents  used  for  CC  were  of  analytical  grade  (Shanghai  Chemical  Reagents  Co.,  Ltd.  China),  and  solvents  used  for  HPLC  were  of  HPLC  grade  (J  &  K  Scientific

used  for  CC  were  of  analytical  grade  (Shanghai  Chemical  Reagents  Co.,  Ltd.  China),  and  solvents  used  for  HPLC  were  of  HPLC  grade  (J  &  K  Scientific  Ltd.).  Fractions  were  monitored  by  TLC  under  UV  light,  and  spots  were  visualized  by  heating  silica  gel  plates  sprayed  with  10%  H2SO4 in EtOH. NCI-H1975 cancer cell line was obtained from  ATCC; HTRF KinEASE-STK S3 kit was purchased from Cisbio  Bioassays (Codolet, France).

4.2. Microorganism material  The  strain  Streptomyces  sp.  SS17F  was  obtained  from  a  marine sediment sample collected near ShengSi Island (Zhejiang  Province  of  China)  by  using  standard  dilution  plating  method.  16S  RNA  gene  sequence  showed  the  strain  shared  99%  identity  with Streptomyces albolongus. A voucher strain (Streptomyces sp.  SS17F)  was  preserved  at  the  Laboratory  of  Institute  of  Marine  Biology, Ocean College, Zhejiang University, China.  4.3. Extraction and isolation  In  order  to  obtained  novel  compounds,  the  strain  was  re-cultured  at  28℃  on  rice  solid  medium  (40g  rice  with  60mL  saline water (25 g sea salt dissolved in 1 L water), autoclaved for  20  min  at  121℃)  in  500  mL  Erlenmeyer  flask  for  1  month.  We  prepared  500  flasks  and  finally  all  the  fermented  medium  was  extracted thrice using EtOAc. The extract was concentrated under

reduced  pressure  to  yield  a  black  matter  (46.0  g).  The  black  matter  was  resolved  in  90%  MeOH-H2O  (90:10,  v/v)  and  then  the  extracted  methanol-water layer was concentrated to give the crude extract  (27.4  g).  The  crude  extract  was  separated  by  a  column  of  silica  gel  eluted  with  CH2Cl2/MeOH  (50:1  to  1:1)  to  obtain  ten  fractions (D1-D10). Then D10 was subjected to Sephadex LH-20  column  chromatography,  using  CH2Cl2/MeOH  (1:1,  v/v)  as  mobile  phase  to  give  eight  fractions  (D2a-D2h).  D2c  was  separated  into  five  fractions  (D3a-D3e)  by  MPLC  using  a  step  gradient  elution  of  MeOH-H2O  (20%-100%,  80  min,  15.0  mL/min),  and  D3d  was  then  further  separated  by  preparative  HPLC  (28:72:0.05  CH3CN-H2O-TFA,  10.0  mL/min)  to  afford  compounds 1-4 (compound 1 13.0 mg, tR = 34 min; compound 2  11.3 mg, tR = 36 min; compound 3 3 mg, tR = 23 min; compound  4 5.8 mg, tR = 25 min;).

Compound  4  (2.0  mg)  was  dissolved  in  a  mixture  of  dichloromethane (10 mL) and triethylamine (5 µL). The mixtures  were stirred at room temperature for 5 min, and then either (S)-  (R)-α-methoxy-α-(trifluoromethyl)  phenylacetyl  chloride  or  (MTPA-Cl,  15  µL)  was  added  gradually.  The  reaction  was  terminated with H2O (5 mL) after 10 h, and then the water phase  was extracted with equal volume dichloromethane three times at  room  temperature  and  organic  phase  was  dried  under  reduced  pressure  to  give  a  residue.  (R)-MTPA  ester  (4R,  1.0  mg,  tR  7.2  min)  or  (S)-MTPA  ester  (4S,  1.2  mg,  tR  8.0  min)  was  obtained  (mobile  phase:  from  MeCN/H2O,  30/70;  flow  rate:  1.0  mL/min;  UV  detection:  254  nm). 4.6. Cytotoxicity assay.    The cytotoxicity against Human lung adenocarcinoma cell line  H1975 was evaluated using cell counting kit-8 (DOjinDo, Japan)  assay.  H1975  cells  were  grown  in  1640  medium  with 10%  FBS  and seeded at a density of 6×103 cells per 200µL per well in a 96  well  plate,  and  incubated  for  24  h.  After  that,  cells  were  treated  with the indicated concentration of compounds for 24 h. Then 10  µL of CCK-8 was added to each well of the plate and incubated  for  1−4  h,  the  absorbance  at  450  nm  was  measured  using  Varioskan Flash Multimode Reader (Thermo Scientific, USA).  4.7.
